    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

    <insight>
        <p>
            Logarithmic equations are powerful tools that can help us understand and solve a wide range of real-life problems, from population growth to sound intensity. By applying logarithmic properties and calculations, we can make sense of complex phenomena and make informed decisions based on data.
        </p>
    </insight> 

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
         <p>
            A bacterium population doubles every <m>3</m> hours. If the initial population is <m>100</m>, how many bacteria will there be after <m>24</m> hours? Use logarithms to solve this problem.
         </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Let <m>P(t)</m> be the population at time <m>t</m> hours. We can express the population growth as:
            </p>
            <p>
               <m>P(t) = P_0 \times 2^{t/3}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Where <m>P_0</m> is the initial population <m>(100)</m>and <m>t</m> is the time in hours. We want to find <m>P(24)</m>:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>P(24) = 100 \times 2^{24/3} = 100 \times 2^8 = 100 \times 256 = 25600</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, after <m>24</m> hours, there will be <m>25,600</m> bacteria.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The intensity of a sound is measured in decibels (dB) and is given by the formula:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>I = 10 \times log_{10}(P/P_0)</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Where <m>I</m> is the intensity in decibels, <m>P</m> is the power of the sound, and <m>P_0</m> is the reference power (the threshold of hearing). If a sound has a power of <m>1</m> watt and the reference power is <m>10^{-12}</m> watts, what is the intensity of the sound in decibels?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Substituting the values into the formula:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>I = 10 \times log_{10}(1 / 10^{-12}) = 10 \times log_{10}(10^{12}) = 10 \times 12 = 120</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, the intensity of the sound is <m>120</m> decibels.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A radioactive substance decays at a rate proportional to its current amount. If the half-life of the substance is <m>5</m> years, how long will it take for a sample of <m>100</m> grams to decay to <m>25</m> grams? Use logarithms to solve this problem.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Let <m>P(t)</m> be the amount of the substance at time <m>t</m> years. The decay can be modeled as:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>P(t) = P_0 \times (1/2)^{t/5}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Where <m>P_0</m> is the initial amount <m>(100</m> grams) and <m>t</m> is the time in years. We want to find <m>t</m> when <m>P(t) = 25</m>:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>25 = 100 \times (1/2)^{t/5}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Dividing both sides by 100:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>0.25 = (1/2)^{t/5}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Taking the logarithm base 2 of both sides:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>log_2(0.25) = t/5</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Since <m>log_2(0.25) = log_2(1/4) = -2</m>:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>-2 = t/5</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Multiplying both sides by 5:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>t = -10</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Since time cannot be negative, we take the absolute value:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>t = 10</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, it will take <m>10</m> years for the sample to decay to <m>25</m> grams.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

